&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;real and inverted&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The image formed on the retina of the human eye is&lt;strong&gt; real and inverted&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The retina comprises specialized cells that are sensitive to light, known as &lt;strong&gt;rod and cone cells&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;These cells get stimulated and send signals to the &lt;strong&gt;brain&lt;/strong&gt;, which turns them into erect images that allow us to see.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The lens system of an eye forms an image on a light-sensitive screen known as the &lt;strong&gt;retina&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Light enters the eye through a thin membrane known as the &lt;strong&gt;cornea&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Behind the cornea, there is a structure known as the&lt;strong&gt; iris&lt;/strong&gt;. Its major function is to control the size of the pupil.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;https://storage.googleapis.com/tb-img/production/20/06/F1_J.K_Madhu_23.06.20_D3.png&quot; style=&quot;height: 217px; width: 330px;&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

The correct answer is&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Option 2&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li style=&quot;list-style-type: none; background: transparent; border: 0px; margin: 0px; outline: 0px; padding: 0px;&quot;&gt;&lt;b style=&quot;background: transparent; border: 0px; margin: 0px; outline: 0px; padding: 0px;&quot;&gt;Pole (P/O)&lt;/b&gt;: Geometric center of the spherical surface of the mirror.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li style=&quot;list-style-type: none; background: transparent; border: 0px; margin: 0px; outline: 0px; padding: 0px;&quot;&gt;&lt;b style=&quot;background: transparent; border: 0px; margin: 0px; outline: 0px; padding: 0px;&quot;&gt;Centre of curvature (C)&lt;/b&gt;: Centre of the sphere of which the&amp;nbsp;mirror is a part.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li style=&quot;list-style-type: none; background: transparent; border: 0px; margin: 0px; outline: 0px; padding: 0px;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Focus point&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: bolder; font-family: var(--bs-body-font-family); font-size: var(--bs-body-font-size); text-align: var(--bs-body-text-align);&quot;&gt;:&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;background-color: transparent; font-family: var(--bs-body-font-family); font-size: var(--bs-body-font-size); font-weight: var(--bs-body-font-weight); text-align: var(--bs-body-text-align);&quot;&gt;The point&amp;nbsp;where incident&amp;nbsp;rays parallel to the principal axis meet or seem to be met.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;list-style-type: none; background: transparent; border: 0px; margin: 0px; outline: 0px; padding: 0px;&quot;&gt;&lt;img alt=&quot;Define the principal focus of a concave mirror.&quot; src=&quot;https://images.collegedunia.com/public/image/I1_ff9111ab56f7656fcc6e01acf00873db.png&quot; style=&quot;height: 163px; width: 250px;&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li style=&quot;list-style-type: none; background: transparent; border: 0px; margin: 0px; outline: 0px; padding: 0px;&quot;&gt;For a small spherical mirror,&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);  &quot;&gt;the &lt;strong&gt;principal focus &amp;lsquo;F&amp;rsquo;&lt;/strong&gt; lies exactly at the midpoint of the&lt;strong&gt; pole P&lt;/strong&gt; and the&lt;strong&gt; center of curvature C.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li style=&quot;list-style-type: none; background: transparent; border: 0px; margin: 0px; outline: 0px; padding: 0px;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);  &quot;&gt;Therefore,&amp;nbsp;the focal length of a spherical mirror (concave or convex) is equal to half of its radius of curvature.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li style=&quot;list-style-type: none; background: transparent; border: 0px; margin: 0px; outline: 0px; padding: 0px;&quot;&gt;Or, The distance between the pole and the center of the curvature is twice the distance between the pole and the focus.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li style=&quot;list-style-type: none; background: transparent; border: 0px; margin: 0px; outline: 0px; padding: 0px;&quot;&gt;This means if&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;R = distance between the center of the curvature and the pole (Radius of curvature), f = distance between the focus point and the center of curvature (focal length).&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li style=&quot;list-style-type: none; background: transparent; border: 0px; margin: 0px; outline: 0px; padding: 0px;&quot;&gt;Then&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;R = 2f.&lt;strong&gt;​&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;list-style-type: none; background: transparent; border: 0px; margin: 0px; outline: 0px; padding: 0px;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li style=&quot;list-style-type: none; background: transparent; border: 0px; margin: 0px; outline: 0px; padding: 0px;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Some other useful terms -&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li style=&quot;list-style-type: none; background: transparent; border: 0px; margin: 0px; outline: 0px; padding: 0px;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Principal Axis -&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);  &quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;the straight line passing through the center of curvature C and pole P of a spherical mirror, produced on both sides.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li style=&quot;list-style-type: none; background: transparent; border: 0px; margin: 0px; outline: 0px; padding: 0px;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);  &quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Aperture -&lt;/strong&gt; The portion of a mirror from which the reflection of light actually takes place is called the aperture of the mirror. It is also called the linear aperture of the mirror. The aperture of a spherical mirror is denoted by the diameter of its reflecting surface.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li style=&quot;list-style-type: none; background: transparent; border: 0px; margin: 0px; outline: 0px; padding: 0px;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);  &quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Types of spherical mirror -&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li style=&quot;list-style-type: none; background: transparent; border: 0px; margin: 0px; outline: 0px; padding: 0px;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);  &quot;&gt;&lt;em&gt;&lt;strong&gt;There are two types of spherical mirrors -&amp;nbsp;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li style=&quot;list-style-type: none; background: transparent; border: 0px; margin: 0px; outline: 0px; padding: 0px;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);  &quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;1&lt;/strong&gt;. Convex Spherical Mirror:&amp;nbsp;whose inner (cave type) surface is silvered and reflection takes place at the outer (convex) surface.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li style=&quot;list-style-type: none; background: transparent; border: 0px; margin: 0px; outline: 0px; padding: 0px;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;2.&lt;/strong&gt; Concave Spherical Mirror:&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);  &quot;&gt;whose outer bulged surface is silvered and reflection takes place from the inner hollow (cave type) surface.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;list-style-type: none; background: transparent; border: 0px; margin: 0px; outline: 0px; padding: 0px;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);  &quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Uses of the concave&amp;nbsp;and concave mirror -&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;img alt=&quot;Applications of convex mirrors and concave mirrors worksheet | Live  Worksheets&quot; src=&quot;https://www.liveworksheets.com/sites/default/files/styles/worksheet/public/def_files/2020/11/16/1116045728924296/1116045728924296001.jpg?itok=kW2lK4Fh&quot; style=&quot;height: 346px; width: 245px;&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;White light is made of all seven colors of the rainbow which can be seen when the white light is passed through a prism.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul style=&quot;list-style-type:disc&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The colors are red, orange, yellow, green, blue, indigo and violet.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The correct answer is&lt;strong&gt; 90&amp;deg;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul style=&quot; list-style-type: disc;&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Total&amp;nbsp;internal&amp;nbsp;reflection&amp;nbsp;(TIR)&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;occurs at the interface of&amp;nbsp;two transparent media&amp;nbsp;when the ray of light travels from a&amp;nbsp;denser medium to a rarer medium.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;critical angle&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;is the angle of&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;incidence&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;in the denser medium for which&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;the angle of refraction&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;in the&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;rarer medium&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;is&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;90&amp;deg;&lt;/span&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Total&amp;nbsp;internal&amp;nbsp;reflection&amp;nbsp;(TIR)&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;of light is the&amp;nbsp;reflection&amp;nbsp;of light&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;within the same medium&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;when a ray of light is incident&amp;nbsp;at the interface of two media at an&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;angle of incidence which is greater than the critical angle&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;for the pair of media i.e.&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;i &amp;gt;i&lt;span style=&quot;position: relative; line-height: 0; vertical-align: baseline; bottom: -0.25em;font-size:10.5px;&quot;&gt;c&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;EXPLANATION:&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul style=&quot; list-style-type: disc;&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;From above it is clear that the&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;critical angle&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;is the angle of&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;incidence&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;in the denser medium for which&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;the angle of refraction&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;in the&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;rarer medium&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;is&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;90&amp;deg;&lt;/span&gt;. Hence, option 1&amp;nbsp;is correct.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
